and develop algorithms to fuse and/or correlate the data provided by these sensors in support of missile defense and space C2
missions.

Will utilize SwECoP to modernize and govern all enterprise software development. The SwECoP will establish adaptive software
engineering practices and standards, such as MOSA, containerization, DevSecOps, Agile, and Scrum, and manage an Missile
Defense System-Next Software integration capability to accelerate the rapid development of critical capabilities like C2BMC. This
approach enables the rapid integration of a global sensor network, enhances defense against advanced hypersonic threats, and
ensures continuous, automated testing and validation across the lifecycle of the System of Systems.

Software in the Cloud (SWiC) funding enables rapid delivery, continuous improvement, and sustained operation of mission
software through secure, accredited cloud environments. This approach allows software capabilities to be updated, scaled, and
integrated across the enterprise at operational tempo without system redesign or extended downtime. By leveraging modular
architectures and modern software practices, SWiC accelerates capability insertion, improves mission availability, and reduces
lifecycle risk while maintaining required cybersecurity and compliance standards.

C2BMC will analyze existing systems capability to defend against Glide Phase Interceptor threats and upgrade existing systems
to support hypersonic missile defense activities.


