Description: PTS-G includes the engineering, development and manufacturing of payload and satellites with X-band and military
Ka-band transponder communication capability and ground infrastructure to include anchor stations that will connect into existing
Protected Anti-jam Tactical SATCOM (PATS) infrastructure developed under the PTES program. Includes ground and software
modifications required beyond the PTES baseline in order to interface with PTS-G segments. Includes ground development,
modifications, and/or services for satellite operations. PTS-G is expected to use existing PTW-capable user modems, but it may
also support transponded communications with other modems. PTW modems for user terminals will be acquired by each Service
and by international partners.

FY 2025 Plans:
The program office released the PTS-G RFP for design and flatsat demonstration work, resulting in a mature system design
review, targeting a new start contract award in 3rd Quarter FY 2025. The program office will also procure Joint Hub modems to
enable future ground connectivity, refine financial and schedule considerations, finalize system requirements and designs, and
begin design, demo, engineer, manufacture, and test 4 SVs (2 Ka, 2 X).
FY 2026 Plans:
The Program Office is working towards the first delivery order for up to four contractors for the design and development of PTS-
G vehicles (driving competition among vendors to deliver SVs along with X-band and Ka-band payloads). This would be followed
by the EMD award, and second delivery order, for four vehicles. The program office will continue to design, demo, engineer,
manufacture, and test 4 SVs (2 Ka, 2 X), and procure Joint Hub modems to enable future ground connectivity. PTS-G will have
two efforts; one for X-Band production and another for mil Ka-Band production. FY 2026 activities include a Delta Critical Design
Review and SV production start for both the bus and payload, and parts buy in preparation for ground integration. Rapidly respond
to implement system resiliency and situational awareness necessary to operate in the contested space domain. Activities may
include, but are not limited to program office support, studies, technical analysis, experimentation, prototyping, and activities that
may leverage commercial and international opportunities.
FY 2025 to FY 2026 Increase/Decrease Statement:
FY 2026 increased to support the first year of production of four Space Vehicles. These activities include design, engineering,
integration, and manufacturing activities.
