B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                  FY 2024    FY 2025      FY 2026
enhance system response and resiliency to operate in the contested space domain based on aggressive threats by our pacing-
competitors, China and Russia. By incorporating these data sources, GBOSS strengthens its ability to support multiple stages of
the GEO Kill Chain, particularly in the Find, Fix, and Track phases. GBOSS improves resolution, sensitivity, search rate, tracking
of non-cooperative launches, precise tagging of clustered objects, detection of closely spaced dim objects, attribution of orbital
attackers and delivers foundational technology to support data exploitation for advanced indications and warnings. This effort
includes upgrading existing sensors and dissemination of all data to DoD and IC stakeholders via the Unified Data Library (UDL).
Collaboration with allies on shared optical capabilities is integral to GBOSS, enabling a more comprehensive and resilient SDA
architecture.

FY 2025 Plans:
Completed contractor verification, developmental, and operational testing of the GEODSS Enhanced Tower (GET) upgrade at
the WSMR GEODSS site leading to operational acceptance. Packaged and shipped material, and completed installation of GET
towers at the GEODSS Maui site. Invested in commercial data to bolster United States Indo-Pacific Command (USINDOPACOM)
efforts and to mitigate coverages in the Atlantic gap.
FY 2026 Plans:
Complete contractor verification, developmental, and operational testing of the GEODSS Enhanced Tower (GET) upgrade at
the Maui GEODSS site leading to operational acceptance. Conclude investigating the use of passive RF capabilities to enhance
the optical sites contribution to support multiple stages of the GEO Kill Chain, particularly in the Find, Fix, and Track phases.
Complete investment in commercial data to bolster United States Indo-Pacific Command (USINDOPACOM) efforts and to mitigate
coverages in the Atlantic gap, further bolstering the GEO Kill Chain by enhancing space object tracking and characterization.
Complete initial exploration into using commercial data to bolster United States Indo-Pacific Command (USINDOPACOM)
efforts and mitigate coverages in the Atlantic sensor coverage gap, with a focus on incorporating passive RF capabilities to
strengthen the GEO Kill Chain. FY 2026 funding will allow the program office to rapidly respond to urgent needs by developing
and implementing the system resiliency and domain awareness capabilities necessary to operate in the contested space domain.
Activities may include, but are not limited to program office support, studies, technical analysis, experimentation, prototyping,
and activities that may leverage commercial, U.S. Government partnership, and international opportunities to respond to existing
and emerging adversarial threats with speed and agility, further bolstering the GEO Kill Chain through enhanced space domain
awareness.
FY 2025 to FY 2026 Increase/Decrease Statement:
Decrease of $49.951M for GBOSS reflects program completion and a transfer of funding which will be sourced from the
Reconciliation Bill (H.R. 1) upon enactment.
