A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
Space Domain Awareness (SDA) is one of five core competencies of the Space Force and is the effective identification, characterization, and understanding of any
factor, passive or active, associated with the space domain that could affect space operations and thereby impact the security, safety, economy, or environment of our
nation. As the foundation for space control, SDA encompasses surveillance of all space objects and activities; detailed surveillance of specific space assets; monitoring
space environmental conditions; monitoring cooperative space assets; gathering indications and warning on adversary space operations; and conducting integrated
command, control, communications, processing, analysis, dissemination, and archiving activities.

This program element develops, tests, upgrades and fields new SDA capabilities across the space surveillance network (SSN) while companion program element
1203940SF develops, fields, and operationalizes sensor networks and information integration capabilities. Activities funded in this program element (1206425SF) also
support efforts such as engineering studies and analyses, architectural engineering studies, trade studies, technology needs forecasting, modernization initiatives,
systems engineering, system development, and test & evaluation. Activities may include prototyping and technology demonstration(s).

Deep Space Advanced Radar Capability (DARC) is a ground-based, SDA radar system that detects, tracks, and maintains custody of deep space objects 24/7 in all
weather and through the solar exclusion gap. DARC will augment the Space Surveillance Network as an additional sensor with increased capacity and capability for
deep space object custody, providing full global coverage.

DARC Site 1 was initially awarded as a Middle Tier Acquisition (MTA) Rapid Prototype. On 22 May 2024, the Service Acquisition Executive (SAE) approved successful
completion of the DARC Site 1 prototype and transitioned the program to be a Major Capability Acquisition (MCA) to complete development and operationally field
DARC Sites 1 (Australia), Site 2 (United Kingdom), and Site 3 (United States).

The FY 2026 request for DARC includes $0 thousand discretionary funds and $281,861 thousand of mandatory (reconciliation) for a total of $281,861 thousand. The
mandatory funds continue construction and integration of Site 1, and development of Site 2. Further information for this reconciliation request is provided in Section
20009 (INDOPACOM Capabilities) of the Reconciliation Exhibit.

This program element may include necessary civilian pay expenses required to manage, execute, and deliver DARC weapon system capability. The use of such
program funds would be in addition to the civilian pay expenses budgeted in program elements 1206392SF and 1206398SF.

