Note
This program, BA 5, PE 1206771SF, project 650008, CASR, is a new start.

A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
Commercial Services delivers integrated, effective, efficient, and resilient commercial space capabilities to the warfighter in support of OSD's Commercial Space
Integration Strategy and USSF's Commercial Space Strategy. It determines capability needs in USSF mission area architectures that can and should be fulfilled with
commercial capabilities, identifies and integrates viable commercial solutions, and ensures the reliability, availability, resiliency, cybersecurity, operational utility and
interoperability of the commercial capability to be presented to the space operators, military warfighters, and combatant commands. It ensures commercial capabilities
will be available in peacetime and through the entire spectrum of conflict. The Commercial Space Office (COMSO) leads USSF efforts to develop sufficient and efficient
capabilities by integrating commercial capabilities into hybrid (government, commercial, allied) architectures.

Project 650008 funds Commercial Augmentation Space Reserve (CASR), a contractually managed framework for building relationships with industry during peacetime
to ensure DoD access to commercial space capabilities throughout the spectrum of conflict. This funding supports the initial establishment and execution of the CASR
program and activities to include contractual integration of commercial providers into CASR framework; threat sharing; wargaming/exercises; readiness and inspection
program of CASR companies; Commercial Space Marketplace for Innovation and Collaboration (COSMIC); and other CASR incentives (security, cyber, protection
measures, etc.).

Project 650009 funds Commercial Capability Integration. With the commercial space industry innovating and developing capability at a record rate, COMSO will leverage
the full force of this innovation by rapidly integrating commercial space capabilities to meet warfighter demand. The near-term focus of this effort is to expand commercial
integration efforts where architecture gaps and current/emerging commercial capabilities match, in areas such as as space sensing and multi-domain awareness,
Space-Based Environmental Monitoring (SBEM), alternate forms of Positioning, Navigation and Timing (alternate PNT), Space Domain Awareness (SDA), and Space
Access, Mobility and Logistics (SAML). Commercial Capability Integration efforts will encompass all USSF mission areas to identify and integrate commercial capabilities
necessary to meet warfighter needs. Leveraging commercial space will allow for cost efficiencies and will expedite delivery of space capabilities to the warfighter.




